{{Infobox book | name = The Bluejacket's Manual | title_orig = | image = Bluejacket manual23.jpg | caption = 23rd Edition Hardcover | author = [[Thomas J. Cutler]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = [[United States|U.S.]] | language = [[English language|English]] | series = | subject = [[United States Navy]] life | genre = Handbook | publisher = [[United States Naval Institute]] Press | release_date = 4 May 2009 (24th Edition) | media_type = Print | pages = 644 (Hardcover 24th edition) | isbn = 978-1-59114-153-2 | isbn_note = (Hardcover 24th edition) | oclc = 262434708 }}
'''''The Bluejacket's Manual''''' is the basic handbook for [[United States Navy]] personnel. First issued in 1902 to teach new recruits about [[naval]] procedures and life and offer a reference for active sailors, it has become the "bible" for Navy personnel, providing information about a wide range of Navy topics. The current version, issued in 2017, is the 25th Edition and is given to all enlistees.<ref name="store">{{cite web | url = https://www.usni.org/store/books/professional-books-sea-services/blue-and-gold-professional-series/bluejackets-manual-25t | title = Bluejacket's Manual, United States Navy |edition=25th | work = [[United States Naval Institute]] | accessdate = 2018-03-23 }}</ref>
== History == Before 1902, the Navy had at least two books for training young men in naval procedure. ''Seamanship'', by Captain [[Alfred Thayer Mahan]], was the primary textbook about [[seamanship]] at the [[United States Naval Academy]] but was not used by [[enlisted]] men; many sailors at the time were still illiterate and in any case, the [[oral tradition]]s and procedures of petty officers were the basis of enlisted sailors' education. ''The Seaman's Handbook'' by [[Lieutenant Commander|LCDR]] [[Stephen B. Luce]], saw general use in the [[United States Merchant Marine|Merchant Marine]], but less in the Navy.<ref name="turns100">{{cite web |url = http://www.news.navy.mil/media/allhands/flash/ah200206/feature2_1.html |title = The Bluejacket's Manual Turns 100 |last = Faram |first = Mark D. (JO1) |work = [[All Hands]] |date = June 2008 |accessdate = 2008-11-02 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20020714153645/http://www.news.navy.mil/media/allhands/flash/AH200206/feature2_1.html |archivedate = 2002-07-14 |df = }}</ref>
1902 saw the first publication of ''The Bluejacket's Manual'', written by [[Lieutenant]] [[Ridley McLean]], as well as the ''Recruit's Handy Book''. Every enlistee received the latter, and by [[World War I]], both were being issued to every recruit. The ''Handy Book'' was discontinued in the 1920s.<ref name="turns100" />
Some manuals published between 1903 and early 1915 have inconsistent edition numbering. The 1903, 1905, 1907 and 1908 were considered the 2nd, 3rd, 4th, and 5th editions by the authors and the Naval Institute. In 1914, Franklin Publishing was contracted to publish the 1914 and 1915 book and pamphlet manuals. Because 1914 was the first time Franklin published the manual, they published their edition as the First Edition, the early 1915 version as the 2nd and the late 1915 one as the 3rd. A single numbering system was restored with the 3rd edition, late 1915 Manual.<ref>{{cite web|last=Weenink|first=R.A.|title=The Bluejacket's Manual|url=http://www.bluejacketsmanual.com/file-BJM/bluejacketsmanual.htm|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>
===Centennial Edition=== The 2002 Centennial Edition, also called the 23rd Edition, saw several modifications, including a reversion to its original title: ''Bluejacket's''.<ref name="store" /> The "Navy Education and Training" chapter was expanded and the "Naval Missions and Heritage" chapter was added.<ref name="store" />
The current (25th) edition's official author is retired [[Commander]] Thomas J. Cutler, who called the work as a "collaborative effort".{{cn|date=March 2018}}
